{
  "texts": [
    "(ii) Responses elicited by the omissions were related to the expectations held by the participants on the presence of the omitted tone, demonstrating that they encode absence prediction error.",
    "This finding constitutes the first unambiguous demonstration of the encoding of absence prediction error in the brain [18,21].",
    "(iii) Absence prediction error was encoded in the MGB and PAC, but not in the IC.",
    "This pattern is distinct from feature prediction error which is strongly encoded in IC [32,34,35,37].",
    "Together, the results suggest that the detection of absence is based on a specific type of prediction error in the human brain and that it is computed by dedicated circuits.A central assumption of predictive coding as grounded in the Free Energy Principle [9,10] (see [38] for a comprehensive review) is that probabilistic representations are Gaussianly distributed (the Laplace assumption)."
  ]
}